loyees, as well as their attitudes toward their jobs and their company. Boeing employees' experience holds vital lessons for other employees, the leaders of other firms determined to thrive in today's era of inescapable and growing global competition, as well as public officials concerned about the well-being of American workers and companies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aIndustrial relations. 0aOrganizational change. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh1 aGrunberg, Leon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMoore, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSikora, Patricia B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300154627423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300154627.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles